column9: The candidate outlined a clear and compelling vision for the future of WIHR.
column10: The candidate demonstrated an understanding of the local and national Humanities landscape.
column11: The candidate was prepared and organized.
column12: The presentation was concise and well-structured.
column13: The candidate offered concrete examples and strategies for WIHR.
column15: Overall, I would rate this presentation as:
column16: What parts of this vision resonate with you and would best move WIHR forward? (please explain)
column17: What parts of this vision do you find unattainable or disagree with? (please explain)
column18: Do you have any ideas about possible WIHR activities not covered in the talk but you would like to pass along?

column16: Collaboration and support for research
How WIHR can support research initiatives, promote and engage through digital and public humanities, and support interdisciplinary scholarship across WY and the world.
column21: This candidate possesses a tremendous amount of experience, knowledge, and passion for interdisciplinary scholarship. She has extensive connections across the humanities disciplines globally.

column16: I think this candidate has more experience working with Humanities initiatives on a state, national, and international level than the other. I think their interest in finding sources is compelling.
column21: The first candidate provided more concrete examples of programming, which as a faculty member I appreciated, but I think that the second is better qualified in terms of experience to lead WIHR

column16: The emphasis on collaboration seemed to be a core value that should indeed drive WIHR.
column17: The repeated focus on faculty support was appreciated, but WIHR has a broader, state-wide vision. By contrast, Dr. Morris's presentation covered specifics at all levels (state, Univ., international)

column16: Strengthening relationships within the state to better advocate for the value of humanities research; expanding external funding; "scaled programming" that includes a variety and range of activities
column21: The candidate demonstrated her in-depth knowledge of state, national, and international contexts; her experience and wisdom would allow her to hit the ground running.

column16: Dr. Sailor's understanding and expressed support for faculty at their various stages is critical. She acknowledges funding, but more importantly mentorship and community- and the same for students.
column21: I value Dr. Sailor's array of experience and know first hand she pays gained knowledge and skill set forward.

column16: Rachel was realistic about what WIHR is and can become.  This perspective comes from years of engagement with the interdisciplinary humanities at UW and with colleagues from around the nation/world.
column17: This is no criticism of her but a challenge to the humanities at UW:  how to interact with larger humanities communities in WY and the US without enlisting in the academic version of The Hunger Games.
column18: I suspect that Rachel is thinking of this but didn't have time to mention:  international fellowships.  Also, the possibility of humanities internships related to (public) research projects.
column21: Rachel is a superior candidate, rooted in experience at UW/WIHR.  She has a strong research record and has created a network of colleagues worldwide.  She is the creative director we need.

column16: I could not find the thread that would connect this vision. Overall left underwhelmed by her presentation.
column17: It is all attainable, but not visionary. I believe Dr. Morris presented a much more compelling vision & plan and for these reasons, Dr. Sailor's vision felt weak and uninspiring.
column18: I was unclear on how WIHR would really work to serve the state beyond the university. As a land-grant school, that needs to be a part of our vision in all elements of our work.
column20: I do not know either candidate personally or professionally, but have worked with WIRH. I did not get the sense that Dr. Sailor would be the person to lead WIRH in this moment. Her vision was narrow.
column21: WIRH should not simply be research generating, but balance with showcasing the societal impacts of this work to wide audiences. Appreciating humanities research by the public should be a goal too.

column16: I have a background in philanthropy and Rachel's take on an increase in donor giving and fundraising opportunities are spot on. She's focused on diversified funding streams and sustainability, VIP.
column17: I think it's a strange time to be ambitious, so growth may not be possible with the uncertainty of the new admin. I do think that Rachel is capable of keeping the program afloat/weathering this storm.

column16: I liked their ideas for supporting faculty and student projects and research. I liked that there was forethought in considering funding in the current climate.
column17: There was not anything that I specifically disagreed with she had good ideas all the way around.

column16: Very standardized goals, however, Dr. Sailor had some great ideas in elevating the profile of scholars such as awards and recognition and building stronger partnerships with WY cultural organizations.
column17: While Dr. Sailor mentioned that the WIHR is the place to have discussion about the effects and impacts of anti-DEI state and federal legislation, there was no suggestions on how WIHR can participate.
column18: Offer funding for faculty to teach study abroad, launch a WIHR publication journal easy reader magazine, WIHR is a high brow intellectual organ., we need to make WIHR accessible to diff audiences.

column16: Rachel's adaptable approach to the changing humanities landscape is commendable, especially in regards to addressing funding challenges.
column18: As Rachel pointed out, the Libraries is an incredible resource for humanities, particularly the DSC and digital collections. We would like to have a more solid collab/partnership with WIHR.

column16: Strongest on detail in the area of public humanities engagement but I'm not convinced this is the top priority given the current research landscape.
column17: I didn't see a clear strategy for cultivating a culture of grantspersonship in the humanities. Optimism for new foundations/donors is not yet supported in what we're seeing on the national level.
column18: Specific strategies are needed for supporting 1. basic humanities research through supporting grant writing and engagement and 2. strategy for cultivating larger scale projects.
column20: I worry that the candidate has had many opportunities ie international work, 2fellowships, Seibold, HCI, but did not articulate how they shape her vision for WIHR or could benefit UW institutionally.
column21: This felt like a WIHR 1.0 approach to cultivating morale and supporting faculty who are already in the WIHR sphere. I was looking for clearer examples, lessons learned, and ambitious vision and plan.

Both candidates would make good leaders, but given that Morris just recently earned tenure and Sailor is a full professor, I think Sailor is the best choice for Director. Morris should be Assist. Dir.

column16: Dr. Sailor brings experience and has been with the University of Wyoming for a long time. That is an important consideration and something to appreciate in moments of uncertainty.
column17: I thought that some of Dr. Sailor's answers were a bit general and broad. I would have liked to hear more specifics concerning international goals and connections to faculty research.
column20: I suppose that I found her answers more general than the other finalist.

column16: Awareness and connection with many humanities leaders
column17: Not detailed enough, seems to general and unaware of current "fan base" of humanities practicioners on campus. Not strategic enough mention of REDD and need to develop a strong relationship with it.
column18: I like other candidate's more detailed focus with specific suggestions such as yearly changing themes.
column20: More backward looking than forward looking. Not enough detail.

column16: I appreciate that Dr. Sailor defines humanities in broad and adaptable ways. I like the ECTL model, Board of Advisors, and her grant writing expertise.
column21: I appreciate that we have had two highly qualified candidates with solid visions.

column16: Rachel’s existing experience with Humanities funding and organizing bodies (NEH, CHCI) will be invaluable for WIHR going forward. She already has the connections the Institute needs.
column21: Of the two candidates, my vote is for Rachel.

column16: Dr Sailor promised to be effective at interacting with donors and lawmakers in the state. She articulated a compelling vision for the public and Wyoming-focused humanities.
column17: I thought she emphasized public humanities at the expense of my traditional humanities, when both are important. Compared to Dr Morris, Dr Sailor had a less energizing and inspiring vision for WIHR

column16: Dr Sailor had a very broad and expansive view of the humanities which I agree with.
column17: Dr Sailor discussed plans that were very ambitious and, though she mentioned funding opportunities, it wasn’t clear that she would be able to fund all of her plans.
